{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_morton_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600131/1929120601/0532.xml":{"full_text":"RETAIL BUSINESS\nHAVING 818 YEAR\nDepartment Stores to Pass\n1928 Record, Says Alfred\nB. Koch at Survey.\nAn optimistic view of the department\nStore trade was presented yesterday\nafternoon at the national business sur\n\u00bbey conference by Alfred B. Koch, presi\ndent of the National Retail Dry Goods\nAssociation, who analyzed the situation\nas Indicating that the annual volume\nof business this year will surpass the\nvolume of 1928 on a dollar basis.\nWith the holiday business off to a\ngood start. Mr. Koch pointed out, it is\ngenerally believed that retail trade will\nbe up to normal expectations. The\nspread of increased business, he pre\ndicted, would be general, except possi\nbly in those districts which may ex\nperience local depressions due to un\nforeseen industrial conditions.\n\"Since 1920 department stores have\nseen the wisdom of adopting a policy\nof conservative merchandising, because\nof changing conditions, particularly in\nthe realm of consumer demand and the\nimportance of the style factor in mer\nchandise\u201d said Mr. Koch. \"The result\nhas been that during this interim\nmanufacturers, wholesalers, Jobbers and\nretailers have adjusted production\nschedules and stocks of merchandise on\nhand to mpet these new conditions.\nHence, at the present time while there\nare ample stocks on hand to satisfy the\nnormal wants of consumers, our' dis\ntributive outlets are not carrying in\ntheir warehouses the large inventories\nof merchandise which proved to be so\ndisastrous to them in 1920. We believe\nthat this is a condition which will be an\nImportant factor in the stabilizing of\ngeneral business conditions and In the\nmaintenance of our national prosperity.\nOctober Sales Larger.\n\u201cThe latest figures available, showing\nthe trend of department store sales,\nissued by the Federal Reserve Board on\nNovember 26. show that sales for the\nmonth of October for the country as a\nwhole were 3 2 per cent larger than in\nOctober, 1928. This figure was com\npiled as the result of statistics received\nfrom 523 stores located in 229 cities.\nInventories of merchandise of reporting\ndepartment stores at the end of October\nwere at the same level as a year ago, ac\ncording to reports from 433 stores.\n\"During the past week reports Indi\ncate that many lines of merchandise\nhave shown substantial increases In\nsales, resulting from cold weather and\nalso due in part to more general con\nfidence in the business outlook. The\nholiday business is off to a good start,\nand tt is now generally believed that re\ntail trade will be up to normal expecta\nams. The distribution of Christmas\nrings funds to the extent of six hun\n\\)RESS-l//>\nfor\nNow is the time to select your Christ-\nYjfiXfjjtt mas Holiday Outfit on easy credit terms.\nChoose from fresh, complete stocks of the smartest '^jggs/\nJfcg* Fifth Ave., New York fashions. Styles that will delight\nISflr the early Christmas shopper. Choose now! Choose better!\nWomen\u2019s Misses\u2019 A\nM C .25rM\nExquisite new 1930 models emphasis\nfIL MEN! All Wool I lH\nJw OVERCOATS LB\njRHBv Just the style, color and BHiCA ll\nj fabric you have wanted at w M Ovl y|jjjjra\nGIRLS\u2019 COATS I BOYS\u2019 O\u2019COATS\nCharming styles made of \u00a3QP B Exceptionally well made q\ndurable fabrics. Many I for warmth, beauty and *Vl\u00ab7u\nlong wear. Easy terms.\nfilin'\ndred million dollars is beginning to be\nfelt m retail channels.\n\"Rumors have been current in many\nquarters that retailers were resorting to\nthe cancellation of orders for merchan\ndise placed with manufacturers and\nwholesalers. During the past few days\nwe have canvassed representative manu\nfacturing resources for such lines as\npiece goods, women\u2019s, misses\u2019 and chil\ndren\u2019s garments, house furnishings,\nshoes, hosiery, costume jewelry, men\u2019s\nclothing and furnishings, gloves and\ntoys, and we have not encountered a\nsingle instance where cancellations were\nreported to be above normal for this\ntime of the year. Where cancellations\ndid exist It was pointed out that they\nwere due to slow delivery of merchan\ndise, error in filling ordeis. or other con\nditions rather than retrenchment on the\npart of retail merchants.\n\u201cIn some rases we learned that re\ntail buyers were adopting a more con\nservative buying policy, but that the\nusual \u2018fill-in\u2019 orders would be antici\npated during the month of December.\nIt is this policy of conservatism both\non the part of retailers and manufac\nturers that is the godsend of the whole\nsituation.\n5.000,000 Retail Employes.\n\"Retailing in the United States nor\nmally gives employment to 5,000,000 peo\nple. While time did not permit the\ncollection of employment statistics in\nthe department store field, we feel that\nwe can safely make the statement that\na census of employes engaged in depart\nment store work would show the num\nber of people on our pay rolls is as great\nas at this time last year. We have been\ninformed that department stores are\nemploying the usual quota of extra peo\nple to take care of the holiday busi\nness. Os course it must be remembered\nthat when the holiday season is over\nsome of these extra employes will\nbe dropped from our pay rolls. This\nhas always been a necessary custom In\nthe past, and when it happens on or\nabout January 1 it should not be in\nterpreted in the sense that merchants\nare reducing their forces in any other\nway than that which is resorted to in\nnormal times.\n\"We believe that department store\nsales and retail sales in general for the\nfirst six months in 1930 wifi equal and\nperhaps surpass retail volume for the\ncorresponding months of 1929. The\nfulfillment of this prediction, however,\ndepends upon the stability of employ\nment, the maintenance of wage sched\nules. the holding of inventories at a\nreasonable conservative level, as well as\nbeing favored with seasonable weather\nconditions, which are an important ele\nment in retail distribution. In addi\ntion, retailing has not been having any\nboom experience. We believe that this\nprediction in regard to retail volume\nlor the first six months of 1930. based\nupon the aforementioned factors, will\nbe universally fulfilled, except in dis\ntricts which may experience local de-\npression due to unforeseen industrial\nconditions or economic changes.\u201d\nTilden Play Flops.\nLONDON, December 8 (i'Pl.\u2014His play\nhaving flopped in the English sticks.\nBill Tilden has a two weeks\u2019 engage\nment as a cabaret entertainer.\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., FRIDAY. DECEMBER 6, 1929.\nWIFE GRANTED WRIT\nAGAINST DIVORCE SUIT\nJustice Wheat Accepts Plea of Mrs.\nWalter Humphries That She Had\nBrought Action Herself.\nJustice Alfred A. Wheat in Equity\nCourt yesterday signed a temporary re\nstraining order enjoining Walter Hum\nphries, manager of a local automobile\naccessories store, from continuing the\nprosecution of a suit for divorce which\nhas been filed in the Cfrcuit Court of\nArlington County. Va.. against Mrs.\nIrene Myrtle Humphries, 215 E street\nsoutheast.\nIn a petition for the restraining order\nMrs. Humphries, represented by Attor\nneys Raymond Neudecker and William\nC. Ashford, told the court she filed suit\nin the local Equity Court a year ago\nfor a limited divorce on the grounds of\ncruelty and desertion, and the case is\nexpected to be reached shortly for trial.\nShe stated that she came to the Dis\ntrict with her husband 10 years ago\nfrom Fredericksburg. Va., and Hum\nphries deserted her in 1920. She fur\nther claims that the Circuit Court of\nArlington County has no jurisdiction\nover the marital differences between\nthem.\nJustice Wheat\u2019s prohibition against\nproceeding in the divorce suit is effec\ntive at once, and the court will later\nhear argument on the question of mak\ning the injunction permanent.\nSeville, Spain, is constructing a large\nairdrome.\nPublic 1\napproval\nIndicates the Quality and merit\nof any com moaity. Every hoar\nof every 24-, over 50,000 sv\ntablets of Grove\u2019s Lax\nalive BROMO\nQUININE are\ntaken for colds\nand headaches\nTry it.\ndfufghu SO\u2022\nGrove\u2019s\nLax a i ire\nBROMO\nQUININE\nTablet 9\nI Jlffc?.. I\nSTAR apmo CO. f\nJERVICE^'k; W' XAL E J\n)f\nWashington\u2019s Largest Radio Stores )f\n409 11th St. N.W. 1350 F St. N.W. 321814th St. N.W. J\nA Timely Value for Xmas Shoppers\n-K\njj Atwater Kent!\nSCREEN-GRID RADIO\nln\nHANDSOME POOLEY CABINET\nDOWN 1\" DOWN\ng W PRICE COMPLETE C\nDELIVERS P 132J2 L R DELIVERS J\nThis RADIO to 1 I T B i TisyI This to\nYour Home Your Home J\nCHECK THESE FEATURES!!!\n1930 Atwater Kent Screen Grid Radio with Electro-Dynamic Speaker\u2014Beautiful Cabinet of walnut\nveneers with maple overlays. Handsomely matched doors. Liberal terms to suit your own budget\nr* offered in Washington only by Star Radio.\n\nDELIVERY NOW OR CHRISTMAS EVE\nyL\nReserve One of These Beautiful Xmas Specials u\nToday\u2014Delivery Can Be Arranged to Suit You yL,\n\nSTAR RADIO SERVICE\nDoes Not Cost EXTRA J\nJ( For 3 Months We Will Service Your Radio FREE yL,\nRegardless of the Number of Calls Necessary\nM Liberal Allowance for Your Old Radio if\nPHONE FRANKLIN 8050 AND SALESMAN WILL CALL\n\u20221* TO APPRAISE YOUR OLD SET\n\n43","height":"25416","width":"19683"}}
